In <em>Coomer v. Lindell</em>, 2025 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 128372 (D. Colo. July 7, 2025), counsel for the defendants included AI-generated citations in their opposition brief to the plaintiff&rsquo;s omnibus motion in limine. During the final pre-trial conference, defense counsel admitted that they &ldquo;ran [the brief] through AI&rdquo; but &ldquo;did not [cite] check&rdquo; the result. Emphasizing that &ldquo;Rule 11 applies to the use of artificial intelligence,&rdquo; the court expressed skepticism that the incident was &ldquo;simply an inadvertent error,&rdquo; held that defense counsel violated Rule 11, and imposed joint and several sanctions of $3,000 on one attorney and his law firm, and individual sanctions of $3,000 on another attorney. Judge Wang declined to sanction the defendants themselves, however, as counsel &ldquo;confirm[ed] that [he] did not advise&rdquo; his clients that he used AI tools in his practice.<br />
<br />
Then, in <em>Coomer v. Lindell</em>, Civil Action No. 22-cv-01129-NYW-SBP, 2026 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 101691 (D. Colo. May 7, 2026), the court observed that the defendants included in their post-trial motions a citation that listed the incorrect court and did not support the proposition for which it was cited.&nbsp; The court again ordered counsel to show cause.&nbsp; In response, the attorney maintained that he did not use GenAI and that &ldquo;the error was minor,&rdquo; And that the &ldquo;circumstances at issue here are not . . . the same type of AI generated error . . . that was the subject of that earlier sanction.&rdquo;&nbsp; The court disagreed that his error was not serious, attributing its pattern to a &ldquo;form of hallucination that has already occurred in this case,&rdquo; and reasoned that a greater sanction than previously was needed to deter this misconduct.&nbsp; The court imposed a $5,000 sanction.&nbsp;
